## **Introduction**

The story of the end of the last Ice Age is one we think we know. Around 20,000 years ago, after a long, deep freeze, the great ice sheets covering the Northern Hemisphere began to melt. Earth was on a slow, steady path to a warmer world—the one in which our own civilization would eventually rise.

But this familiar narrative has a violent, mysterious twist.

Around 12,800 years ago, the warming trend didn’t just stop—it reversed with shocking speed. In a geological blink of an eye, the planet was plunged back into a brutal, near-glacial cold spell known as the&nbsp;**Younger Dryas**. In central Greenland, temperatures plummeted by as much as 9-14°C, with much of that drop occurring “within a single year or less.”

This catastrophic freeze lasted for 1,200 years, coinciding with one of the greatest extinction events in millions of years and the abrupt disappearance of a sophisticated human culture that spanned North America.

For decades, this cataclysm remained a profound enigma. What could have triggered such a swift and devastating climate shift? Today, evidence from across the globe points to a single, controversial suspect: a catastrophic encounter with a fragmented comet. This is the&nbsp;**Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis (YDIH)**, a theory that reframes our planet’s worst cold case not as a mystery solved, but as an ongoing, high-stakes scientific battle over one of the worst days in history.

## **It Wasn’t a Gradual Thaw, It Was a Cataclysmic Freeze**

To grasp the significance of the Younger Dryas, one must understand its sheer violence. Just before the event, the planet was in a relatively warm period known as the Bølling–Allerød interstadial. The Laurentide Ice Sheet was in retreat, and life was adapting to a warming world. Then, the bottom dropped out.

The onset of the cooling was extraordinarily abrupt. As ice cores from Greenland reveal, the temperature there fell between 9°C and 14°C “within a single year or less.” This wasn’t a slow slide back into an ice age; it was a climatic sledgehammer blow. The period gets its name from&nbsp;*Dryas octopetala*, a wildflower adapted to cold, arctic-like conditions, which suddenly flourished across Europe as forests retreated.

This intense cold snap held the Northern Hemisphere in its grip for approximately 1,200 years. Then, just as suddenly as it began, it ended. Around 11,700 years ago, temperatures in Greenland shot up by as much as 10°C in a mere decade.

